 criticized by scholars including Danielle Keats Citron and Frank Pasquale in their work 'The Scored Society' for creating legal uncertainty about defendants' rights to understand and challenge algorithmic assessments.\n\nFourth, it requires that the technical functioning of AI systems be sufficiently documented and auditable. Academic scholars like Mireille Hildebrandt in 'Law for Computer Scientists and Other Folk' argue that legal certainty is incompatible with completely opaque algorithmic systems, as individuals cannot vindicate their rights if they cannot understand how decisions affecting them are made.\n\nWhen legal certainty is absent in AI-enabled public decision-making, several pathologies emerge. Citizens cannot predict how their data will be used or what factors will influence decisions about their welfare benefits, immigration status, or interactions with law enforcement. The Administrative Procedure Act in the United States (5 U.S.C. § 551 et seq.) traditionally requires agencies to provide reasoned explanations for decisions, but as Cary Coglianese and David Lehr argue in 'Regulating by Robot' (Georgetown Law Journal, 2017), algorithmic decision-making can undermine these transparency requirements when systems are too complex to explain or when agencies lack technical capacity to articulate their reasoning.\n\nThe absence of legal certainty manifests in inconsistent application of fundamental rights. For example, research by the AI Now Institute has documented how algorithmic welfare fraud detection systems in various jurisdictions have operated without clear legal authority, explicit accuracy standards, or adequate oversight—leaving recipients unable to understand why benefits were denied or how to effectively appeal.\n\nIt also creates what legal scholar Karen Yeung calls 'hypernudging'—where algorithmic systems shape behavior and allocate resources in ways that are legally consequential but operate below the threshold of traditional legal visibility and accountability. Without clear rules about permissible uses, accuracy requirements, validation procedures, and liability allocation, both public administrators and affected individuals face fundamental uncertainty about their legal rights and obligations.\n\nFrom my perspective as a CEO in this space, legal certainty requires that we can clearly advise public sector clients on compliance obligations, that affected individuals can meaningfully exercise their rights, and that courts can effectively review administrative actions. This means legislation must specify: permissible use cases, data governance requirements, technical standards (such as those being developed by NIST in their AI Risk Management Framework), validation and testing protocols, transparency obligations, human oversight mechanisms, and remedies for harmful errors. Without these elements codified in binding law—not merely soft guidance—we lack the stable, predictable regulatory environment necessary for both rights protection and responsible innovation.",
