in enforceable safeguards for defendants.\n\nTheoretical frameworks like Hart's concept of 'secondary rules' (rules of recognition, change, and adjudication) from *The Concept of Law* clarify that a legal system requires more than primary behavioral rules; it needs institutions to authoritatively identify and enforce them. Applied to AI, an 'enforceable' regulation integrates primary rules (e.g., 'do not deploy prohibited AI practices') with secondary rules establishing regulatory agencies, standards-setting processes, and courts.\n\nTherefore, the transition from aspirational ethics to enforceable law is marked by the incorporation of these elements into binding legal instruments, moving from soft-law frameworks (like the OECD AI Principles) to hard-law legislation (like the EU AI Act).",
