s for their enforcement (e.g., ‘violations are subject to fines by the European AI Office’). This framework is reflected in modern regulatory instruments like the GDPR, where enforceability is achieved through a combination of detailed substantive rules (e.g., data minimization, Article 5), administrative fines (Article 83), and a network of supervisory authorities (Article 51).\n\nPrecedents from other domains further illustrate enforceability. In *Loomis v. Wisconsin* (2016), the U.S. Supreme Court implicitly acknowledged the enforceability of algorithmic accountability by requiring that risk-assessment tools used in sentencing be subject to due process scrutiny, even if it did not prescribe specific regulatory mechanisms. Similarly, the U.S. Federal Trade Commission’s enforcement actions against deceptive AI practices (e.g., *FTC v. Cambridge Analytica*, 2019) demonstrate how existing consumer protection laws can be adapted to enforce AI-related rules, provided there is a clear nexus to unfair or deceptive acts.\n\nTheoretical frameworks like ‘responsive regulation’ (Ayres & Braithwaite, 1992) and ‘experimentalist governance’ (Sabel & Zeitlin, 2010) also inform enforceability in AI regulation. These approaches advocate for tiered enforcement strategies, combining deterrence (e.g., fines) with cooperative measures (e.g., guidance, sandboxes) to balance flexibility and accountability. The EU AI Act’s risk-based classification system embodies this philosophy, with stricter enforcement for high-risk systems and lighter-touch oversight for minimal-risk applications.\n\nUltimately, enforceability hinges on the interplay between legal design and institutional capacity. A rule may be technically binding but unenforceable in practice if regulators lack resources, expertise, or political will (e.g., early GDPR enforcement gaps). Conversely, aspirational rules can gain de facto enforceability if they are incorporated into contracts, industry standards, or corporate governance frameworks (e.g., the NIST AI Risk Management Framework’s adoption by private firms). The challenge for AI governance is to design rules that are both enforceable *and* adaptable to rapid technological change, avoiding the pitfalls of over-regulation or under-enforcement.",

