{
  "response": "Legal certainty in AI-driven public decision-making is the principle that individuals must be able to foresee the legal consequences of actions and understand the rationale behind state interventions. It requires that AI systems operate within transparent, predictable, and non-arbitrary legal parameters, ensuring that the rules governing algorithmic outputs are clear, accessible, and subject to effective judicial review. Specifically, it necessitates 'explicability'—the ability to explain the logic of a decision—and 'contestability,' which allows individuals to challenge algorithmic outcomes. When absent, the system suffers from the 'black box' phenomenon, where the opacity of machine learning models prevents individuals from identifying the legal basis of a decision, effectively stripping them of their right to due process and equality before the law, as the decision becomes an exercise of arbitrary power rather than applied policy.",
