{
  "response": "Accountability in AI governance is defined as the obligation of actors involved in the AI lifecycle—including developers, deployers, and operators—to accept responsibility for the impacts of their systems, to provide transparency regarding system behavior, and to be subject to mechanisms of redress. Accountability is multifaceted: (1) Who: Legal and natural persons exercising control over AI systems (e.g., providers and deployers). (2) For what: The mitigation of risks, compliance with fundamental rights, systemic performance, and unintended harm. (3) To whom: Affected individuals, regulatory bodies, and society at large. This framework integrates ex-ante procedural duties (design and testing) with ex-post mechanisms (remediation and liability).",
