  "response": "Accountability in AI governance is defined as the obligation of actors involved in the AI lifecycle—including developers, deployers, and end-users—to answer for the outcomes of AI systems, justify their decisions, and provide remedies for identified harms. This requires clear traceability (the ability to map outcomes to specific design or operational choices) and answerability (the duty to provide explanations to affected stakeholders and regulatory bodies). Accountability should be hierarchical and distributed: developers remain accountable for safety-by-design and rigorous testing; deployers bear responsibility for operational oversight, bias mitigation, and compliance with usage constraints. Accountability is owed primarily to affected individuals (to protect fundamental rights), regulators (to ensure legal compliance), and society at large (to maintain public trust). It functions as a dynamic mechanism to bridge the 'accountability gap' inherent in complex, opaque algorithmic systems, requiring that liability is neither obscured by technical complexity nor shifted entirely onto automated agents.",
