  "response": "From an industry leadership perspective, enforceability defines the transition from abstract safety principles to measurable operational constraints. An enforceable rule is characterized by 'specification clarity' and 'sanction architecture.' It must provide verifiable metrics—such as model robustness benchmarks, mandatory audit trails, or standardized data lineage requirements—that allow regulators to determine binary compliance or non-compliance. In contrast, aspirational frameworks, such as the voluntary 'Safety Commitments' often seen in high-level policy dialogues, lack the 'legal causality' required to hold entities accountable for specific outcomes. A rule becomes enforceable when it links a defined prohibited action to a specific remedial mechanism or punitive measure, such as the administrative fines found in the GDPR, which created a clear cost-benefit calculus for compliance. We look to the EU AI Act’s tiered risk framework and Article 15 requirements as the benchmark for shifting from 'ethical guidance' to 'legal obligation,' as they establish technical standards (CEN/CENELEC) that translate complex AI behavior into actionable, audit-ready criteria, thereby distinguishing legal mandate from hortatory policy.",
